A '''backup band''' or '''backing band''' is a [[Band (music)|musical ensemble]] that [[Accompaniment|accompanies]] a [[lead singer]] at a live performance or on a [[sound recording|recording]].<ref name="CampbellBrody2008">{{cite book|author1=Michael Campbell|author2=James Brody|title=Rock and roll: an introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RK-JmVbv4OIC&pg=PA191|accessdate=14 December 2010|year=2008|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-0-534-64295-2|pages=191}}</ref>{{better source|date=September 2017}} A backup band can also accompany an instrumental soloist, such as a [[lead guitarist]] or solo [[fiddler]], though [[instrumental music|all-instrumental]] performances, with no singing, are not common in [[popular music]] and [[traditional music]]. This can either be an established, long-standing group that has little or no change in membership, or it may be an [[ad hoc]] group assembled for a single show or a single recording.{{or|date=September 2017}} Ad hoc or "pickup" groups are often made up of [[session musician]]s.
