'''Shaykh <nowiki>'</nowiki>Abbasi''' (active from 1650–1684) was a [[Persia]]n painter known for incorporating [[Western painting|European]] and Indian influences into his illustrations, a practice later adopted by [[Muhammad Zaman]] and [[Aliquli Jabbadar|'Aliquli Jabbadar]]. His style evolved to become more [[Indian art|Indian]] as his career went on – he painted [[Mughal emperors]] and drew particularly Indian heads, using similar techniques. His work has been proposed as evidence of a [[cultural exchange]] between 17th-century Iranian artists and [[Golconda]] artists from the same time period. A total of 25 paintings have been attributed to Shaykh 'Abbasi, including [[illuminated manuscript|illuminations]] from manuscripts and [[Persian miniature|miniatures]] featuring, among other subjects, the [[Safavid]] emperors and the [[Madonna and Child]], colored in pale, transparent tones. Given the activities of contemporaneous artists, it is highly likely that he also painted on objects made from [[papier-mâché]] that was [[lacquer]]ed. He trained his two sons, [['Ali Naqi (painter)|'Ali Naqi]] and [[Muhammad Taqi (painter)|Muhammad Taqi]], in the same style.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title = Shaykh 'Abbasi |editor-last1 = Bloom |editor-first1 = Jonathan |editor-last2 = Blair |editor-first2 = Sheila |work = The Grove Encyclopedia of Islamic Art and Architecture |year = 2009 |publisher = Oxford University Press |isbn = 978-0-19-530991-1 |volume = 3 |pages = 203–04}}</ref>
